## Conclusion

The Gödel case effect is empirically real and replicates reliably under controlled conditions, rejecting the claim that it is a sampling artifact or response-style bias. Neither the brute-vs.-social-fact conceptual ambiguity (Institute 0) nor the bare-NP grammatical form (Institute 2) is the primary driver, as clarifying both ambiguities leaves the cross-cultural effect largely intact. The most likely mechanism combines pragmatic perspective-parsing—East Asian respondents' tendency to resolve ambiguous referents via contextual/pragmatic reasoning rather than rigid designation—with the Gödel case's unique capacity to invite token-vs.-role referential ambiguity. This pragmatic style, documented in cognitive psychology (Nisbett et al. 2001), interacts with the linguistic form (bare NPs in East Asian translation) and conceptual content (brute fact vs. social fact) but is independent of either alone.

