In Korean, bare NPs as well as demonstrative-preceded nominals can serve as an anaphoric definite, sharply contrasting with Mandarin Chinese, where demonstrative-preceded nominals can do so, but bare NPs can do so only in the subject/topic position and not in other positions. This is established. But neither institute predicted or tested the logical consequence: **if grammatical definiteness marking were the driver, Korean (which lacks the Mandarin constraint) should show a *weaker* or *reversed* Gödel effect, not the same magnitude.**

