- **But the native-language test weakens the linguistic hypothesis substantially:** Barry Lam (2010) hypothesized that testing Cantonese speakers in English would artificially bias responses toward descriptivism due to parsing mismatches. However, when Machery et al. (2010) translated the Gödel case into Chinese and retested, the cross-cultural effect *persisted*. East Asian speakers still gave descriptivist responses at rates (~60%) comparable to English-language responses. If the mechanism were purely a parsing artifact from reading English topic-marking incorrectly, the effect should have diminished or disappeared in native Chinese.

- **Descriptive ambiguity confounds the case:** Machery & Askonia (2012) and related work identify that people associate different *types* of descriptions with proper names—brute facts (physical properties) vs. social facts (credit, institutional role). The Gödel case may be peculiarly salient precisely because the distinction between "who actually proved the theorem" (brute fact) and "who got credit" (social fact) is maximally vivid. This ambiguity affects response ratios independent of culture or language structure.

