**The cross-cultural Gödel effect is not explained by a linguistic mechanism rooted in how bare nominals function in classifier languages. Instead, it emerges from an interaction between (1) genuine but modest cross-cultural differences in how descriptions are weighted in reference judgments, and (2) fragility in how the Gödel case itself is framed, translated, and interpreted—particularly ambiguity about whether the "description" refers to a brute fact (who did the work) or a social fact (who bears the name/credit). The linguistic hypothesis failed its operationalized predictions; the cognitive-cultural story remains viable but incomplete.**

