The effect completely disappears in a version of the Gödel case where the narrator's omniscient perspective is not only clarified but made *syntactically and pragmatically central* to every clause (e.g., "We omniscient narrators know that Gödel did the work. In reality, Gödel did the work. Schmidt did not. But John, who doesn't know the real history, believes Schmidt did..."). If cross-cultural variation persists even under this maximally disambiguated framing, my account holds. If it vanishes completely, the Disruptor's parsing hypothesis has more credibility than I've credited.

