- **Directly measure epistemic authority hierarchies in non-philosophical populations.** Design a battery of real-world naming/identification tasks (e.g., "Who is the real founder of Company X?" under conditions of knowledge asymmetry, "What is this artifact really called?" when social convention conflicts with technical precision) with East Asian and Western participants. Measure whether cultural groups differ systematically in which epistemic perspective they privilege, and whether this variation predicts Gödel responses.

- **Construct reference cases pitting different non-causal fact-type pairs** (temporal vs. social; conventional vs. technical; pragmatic vs. historical) and test for cross-cultural differences. This tests whether the mechanism is specific to brute-vs.-social fact weighting or a more general epistemic authority ordering, and whether it generalizes to novel cases.

