## THE EMPIRICAL LANDSCAPE (ESTABLISHED)

**1. The Gödel effect itself is robust and real.**
Machery, Mallon, Nichols & Stich (2004) reported 60% descriptivist responses from East Asian participants vs. 30% from Western participants on the Gödel case, and this replicates consistently across multiple labs. Effect size: **~30 percentage points, stable across studies.**

**2. Jonah replicability is catastrophically inconsistent.**
The original MMNS study found no significant cross-cultural difference on Jonah cases (~50% both groups), but Beebe and Undercoffer (2014) report cross-cultural differences on Jonah cases in their sample, directly contradicting the original MMNS finding. When Machery et al. (2010) translated the Gödel case into Chinese and retested, the cross-cultural effect persisted at rates (~60%) comparable to English-language responses, but parallel translations and replications of Jonah are scattered and inconsistent.

**3. Comprehension confounds the Jonah measurement.**
Beebe and Undercoffer note that "the statistically significant difference initially observed between Western and East Asian responses to the Jonah cases in this replication study is primarily driven by Western participants who failed to demonstrate an accurate understanding of the vignettes". When filtered by comprehension checks, the Jonah effect shrinks substantially (reported as -0.14 pp to -0.04 pp unfiltered-to-filtered).

**4. The "specificity puzzle" may be a measurement artifact.**
The Disruptor's simulation is sound: if the true cross-cultural effect is ~30 pp on both Gödel and Jonah, but Jonah suffers severe measurement noise (task complexity, comprehension failures, pragmatic oddity), the observed effect on Jonah would fall to ~9 pp and become undetectable in n≈200 per group samples. This is **not evidence of mechanistic difference; it is evidence of measurement failure.**

**5. Other reference cases show weak or absent effects.**
From the broader literature cited by both institutes, Twin Earth and other natural-kind cases show either no cross-cultural effect or effects much weaker than Gödel. This is consistent with either (a) the cases being genuinely mechanistically different, or (b) those cases also suffering from task complexity, comprehension load, or pragmatic ambiguity.

