The Gödel effect is real (~25–35 percentage point difference in Kripkean responses) and surgically specific to the Gödel case, not a general artifact of holistic vs. analytic cognition. The primary mechanism is an interaction between (1) the Gödel case's unique embedding of a uniqueness presupposition ("the person who proved incompleteness") in a definite description, and (2) cross-linguistic differences in how this presupposition is pragmatically resolved—English article systems encode uniqueness grammatically, while Mandarin bare nouns require pragmatic resolution under uncertainty. Cognitive style (holistic vs. rule-based reasoning) modulates responses within this presuppositional structure but does not explain the case-specificity. The effect persists in native-language presentations, ruling out a pure parsing artifact, but the failure of Jonah to replicate at similar strength supports a uniqueness-presupposition mechanism rather than a general cognitive one.

