- **The uniqueness-presupposition mechanism predicts the case-specificity.** The Gödel case uniquely hinges on a definite description that presupposes exactly one person satisfies it ("the person who proved incompleteness"). Jonah ("the man swallowed by the whale") does not activate the same uniqueness presupposition—it is about whether a biblical figure exists, not about which unique individual satisfies a description. This distinction is linguistically established (Cheng & Sybesma 1999 on Mandarin bare nouns; Elbourne 2013 on presupposition and definiteness). The Jonah boundary condition confirms this hypothesis: the mechanism is not general to reference questions, but specific to presuppositional structure.

