## The Claim I Will Stake

**The cross-cultural difference in the Gödel case reflects a genuine difference in how speakers weigh *brute-fact descriptions* versus *socially-constructed institutional descriptions* when both are presented as equally definite options.**

Classifier-language speakers (who lack obligatory article marking and have cognitive habits of resolving reference via contextual salience rather than syntactic presupposition) **treat the two descriptions in the Gödel case as equipotent candidates for what "Gödel" picks out in the world**. English speakers, whose grammar forces them to presuppose unique definite identification via articles, fall back on *causal history as a tiebreaker* between two otherwise equivalent definite descriptions.

**This is not holistic vs. analytic cognition.** It is a difference in *what counts as sufficient grounds for reference resolution* when syntax cannot determine it.

The morphosyntactic difference between languages is real and modulating. But it modulates a cognitive difference in *how people resolve ambiguity when the syntax underdetermines reference*—not a difference in how they parse English articles.

