## Conclusion

The cross-cultural Gödel effect is driven primarily by **semantic-pragmatic ambiguity about what kind of descriptions (brute-fact vs. social-fact) can satisfy a name**, not by morphosyntactic differences in how languages mark definiteness. While East Asian languages do permit more flexible definiteness marking than English, the effect persists across linguistic systems because the underlying ambiguity is about *which description type participants privilege when interpreting reference*, not about how participants' native grammars encode specificity. The case-specificity pattern (Gödel effect is stronger than Jonah cases) reflects variation in how much semantic ambiguity each case contains, not a morphosyntactic trigger that activates uniformly across all reference scenarios.

## Confidence

