The cross-cultural effect on the Gödel case is most parsimoniously explained by **language-dependent pragmatic interpretation of the reference question itself**. East Asian speakers, trained by article-poor languages to rely on pragmatic inference rather than explicit grammatical marking, default to interpreting "Who does 'Gödel' refer to?" as a question about **speaker's communicative intent** ("Whose person did the narrator intend to refer to?"), while Western speakers default to a **semantic reference question** ("What does the name semantically pick out by convention?"). The Gödel case is case-specific because it uniquely contains an explicit **reversal of speaker's intent** (first referring to the mathematician, then discovering and switching to Schmidt); a pragmatic interpretation of that reversal naturally yields a descriptivist answer, while a semantic interpretation demands a Kripkean one. The Jonah case lacks this intent-reversal structure, so pragmatic and semantic interpretations converge, eliminating the cross-cultural divergence.

