Both institutes focus on **how descriptions are weighted**, **linguistic morphosyntax**, or **cognitive habits** — but neither examines a brute-fact confound: **"Gödel" is semantically opaque in English and Chinese alike, whereas "Schmidt" is transparent.**

A replication study found 27.8% of Mainland Chinese speakers chose the Kripkean answer in simplified Chinese, with no statistically significant difference from Machery et al.'s original finding of 29% in English (Hong Kong speakers). This **directly falsifies** Institute 0's morphosyntactic parsing hypothesis — the effect persists when tested in the Chinese language itself, meaning it cannot be a trigger-based parsing artifact of English article morphology.

