Machery et al. attempt to explain the discrepancy by appealing to differences between Western and East Asian modes of categorization identified by Nisbett. But these differences fail to explain the conflicting intuitions. The fact that the effect is **case-specific** is itself the refutation of Nisbett: if holistic cognition were the driver, East Asians should give more descriptivist answers across all reference probes equally. They do not.

