There is cultural variation that is extremely robust with children and grown-ups. When done in Asia, in Japan and China, with both grown-ups and 5-7 year-olds, you find the opposite answer — people say the proper name is used to talk about Schmidt. This suggests the effect emerges early via language exposure, **before** formal semantic education or philosophical enculturation, which rules out learned theory but supports automatic linguistic processing.

