The cross-cultural Gödel effect is a genuine linguistic-pragmatic phenomenon, not a methodological artifact, arising from how speakers whose L1 lacks overt definiteness marking (Mandarin, Japanese, Korean, Cantonese) resolve presupposition-threat in English reference contexts. The case-specificity reflects the Gödel case's unique combination of initial presupposition-establishment ("Gödel is famous for the incompleteness theorem") followed by immediate presupposition-violation ("Schmidt actually did the work"). East Asian speakers resolve this threat via descriptive fit rather than causal-historical anchoring—a difference that emerges early in language development and is linguistically, not cognitively, rooted. The effect persists across methodological variations but is amplified by response-style biases (East Asian midpoint selection) that create measurement-method dependence without eliminating the underlying pragmatic mechanism.

