## Key reasons and evidence

- **Case-specificity is robust across studies.** The Gödel case yields consistent cross-cultural differences (Δ ≈ 0.20–0.25, Western 55–87% Kripkean vs. East Asian 31–65%) across Machery et al. (2004), Sytsma & Livengood (2011), Lam (2010 Cantonese), Sytsma et al. (2015 Japanese), and Beebe & Undercoffer (2016). Jonah effects are weaker (Δ ≈ 0.08–0.15), and Twin Earth shows no effect. This rules out global cognitive-style explanations (Nisbett's holism) because a culture-level difference should appear equally across all cases.

