The Gödel effect is real and robust across careful replications, but it is driven primarily by *culturally modulated perspective-taking strategies* in resolving structurally ambiguous experimental probes, not by underlying differences in semantic intuitions about reference itself. The specificity to Gödel reflects the particular combination of two factors: (1) an unavoidable epistemic perspective ambiguity in the original vignettes (the protagonist is misinformed while the narrator is omniscient, creating confusion about which perspective answers the reference question), and (2) a description-type conflict (brute-fact vs. institutional) that interacts with this perspectival asymmetry. Linguistic structure (classifier vs. article languages) and cognitive disposition (perspective-taking habits modulated by cultural norms for collectivism and uncertainty avoidance) jointly determine how speakers resolve this underspecified scenario, but the effect is distinguishable from pure response-style artifacts such as acquiescence bias—though acquiescence remains untested as a confound in the existing literature.

