The cell agrees that (1) the Gödel effect is real, (2) response-style/format matters, and (3) specificity to Gödel requires explanation. 

The disagreement concerns **causation of the response-style bias**: Does the response-style preference for ambiguity arise *because* East Asian languages grammatically underdetermine reference (Disruptor's claim—linguistic structure shapes cognition), or does East Asian response-style bias reflect a general cultural trait of tolerance for ambiguity/contradiction that exists independent of language structure and would persist even if tested in English (Architect's interpretation)? 

