- **Confidence measurement in forced-choice contexts.** Have all participants rate post-choice confidence (1-7 scale: "How confident are you in that answer?"). Hypothesis: East Asian respondents should report significantly lower confidence even when making a binary choice, and confidence should predict shift-to-ambiguous in three-option condition.

- **Presupposition-control replication.** Replicate studies like Ding & Liu (2022) that manipulate whether the description is (a) a brute fact about the referent or (b) a social/observer-dependent fact. Map whether effect size varies by description type, and whether this pattern differs cross-culturally. If cross-cultural difference is insensitive to presupposition type, response format is primary.

- **Developmental study (replication of Starmans & Friedman, 2012).** Test 5-, 7-, and 9-year-olds in both Mandarin-speaking and English-speaking populations on Gödel case with three-option format. If response-confidence artifact is primary, the cross-cultural effect should emerge only in binary forced-choice contexts, not in three-option conditions even at young ages.

