3. **Test linguistic mechanism via language-dominance correlation (Test 3).** Recruit English-fluent East Asian speakers and measure language dominance via the Language Experience and Proficiency Questionnaire (LEPQ) or similar. Regress Gödel case responses on language dominance, cultural background, and their interaction. If linguistic processing is a driver, English dominance should reduce the cross-cultural effect; if not, reject this hypothesis.

4. **Map the case space (Test 4).** Design 4–6 naming probes with varying degrees of brute-fact vs. social-fact ambiguity and context salience (keep narrative prestige constant across probes to isolate ambiguity). Administer all probes to matched East Asian and Western samples. This will establish whether case-selectivity is due to ambiguity structure or to properties unique to Gödel.

