## The Sharpest Claim I'm Willing to Stake

Definite bare nouns in classifier languages are licensed only by uniqueness, while English obligatorily marks definiteness via articles. The Gödel case creates a **presuppositional crisis** for both language groups, but the crisis manifests differently because the presuppositional structure is asymmetric across languages. Translation equivalents in a number of other languages may trigger similar presuppositions, but there has been relatively little detailed study of presuppositions in languages other than English.

**The cross-cultural effect is not a difference in reference semantics or cognitive style. It is a difference in which presuppositional structure licenses the bare nominal form that East Asian speakers must use. The institutes are measuring a methodological confound — presuppositional mismatch in translation — and attributing it to reference theory.**

The test that would kill this hypothesis: Rewrite the Gödel case with explicit presupposition-marking (overt classifier + demonstrative definiteness in Mandarin; explicit "the" + definite article in English) and measure whether the cross-cultural gap collapses. If the gap persists substantially, presupposition is not the driver and one of the existing mechanisms (cognitive style, response format, descriptive ambiguity) must dominate. If the gap shrinks to <5 percentage points, presupposition control has eliminated the effect, and the causal mechanism is linguistic—not what the philosophers thought they were measuring.
